166
00:16:03,135 --> 00:16:05,616
There are many other visual novels with great stories,

167
00:16:05,956 --> 00:16:09,417
philosophical ones, emotional ones, well written mysteries and

168
00:16:09,477 --> 00:16:14,398
human drama. So many to name, but there is one work that

169
00:16:14,518 --> 00:16:16,679
pioneered the visual novel movement.

170
00:16:25,101 --> 00:16:29,462
And that is Kamaitachi no Yoru, translated as the night of the

171
00:16:29,502 --> 00:16:30,142
sickle weasel.

172
00:16:32,670 --> 00:16:37,994
This is actually a game developed by Chunsoft before we merged with Spike and became the

173
00:16:38,054 --> 00:16:38,895
current company.

174
00:16:41,016 --> 00:16:46,681
The original release was in 1994, about 20 years ago, on the SNES.

175
00:16:51,945 --> 00:16:58,491
It is a visual novel, and the plot revolves around two characters who are suddenly drawn

176
00:16:58,631 --> 00:17:01,633
into a horrible murder mystery at a skiing lodge.

177
00:17:02,508 --> 00:17:05,469
You are to solve the mystery and find the murderer.

178
00:17:07,329 --> 00:17:09,610
There is one unique thing about this game.

179
00:17:11,190 --> 00:17:13,751
That is that it doesn't use any flags.

180
00:17:24,814 --> 00:17:28,535
I'm sure everyone here knows what I mean by a flag.

181
00:17:28,715 --> 00:17:31,396
Yes, it's the flag used in computer programming.

182
00:17:34,236 --> 00:17:36,118
Are you going to flirt with Naomi?

183
00:17:36,438 --> 00:17:38,439
If yes, the variable is true.

184
00:17:38,820 --> 00:17:40,881
If no, it will be false.

185
00:17:41,462 --> 00:17:44,384
Soon after, you find out Naomi is your boss's mistress.

186
00:17:45,165 --> 00:17:48,167
So if you chose false, you'll be promoted.

187
00:17:48,948 --> 00:17:51,370
But if you chose true, you'll be fired.

188
00:17:56,835 --> 00:17:58,356
That's a quick example of a flag.

189
00:18:03,760 --> 00:18:08,121
After asking around the development team members who worked on Kamaitachi no Yoru,

190
00:18:08,661 --> 00:18:10,961
it looks like they didn't really use any flags.

191
00:18:14,322 --> 00:18:19,503
If so, how were they able to create branching storylines without losing consistency?

192
00:18:21,244 --> 00:18:25,385
Well, in fact, there are a couple different ways to approach this, but today, I'm going

193
00:18:25,405 --> 00:18:27,425
to talk about the most interesting method.

194
00:18:34,098 --> 00:18:38,619
In Kamaitachi no Yoru, the flags were embedded into the player's brain.

195
00:18:40,279 --> 00:18:43,580
So what exactly does this mean, you're probably thinking.

196
00:18:44,780 --> 00:18:46,701
Don't worry, I'll explain what it means.

197
00:18:56,943 --> 00:18:59,783
Here's a snapshot of the branching narrative structure.

198
00:19:01,705 --> 00:19:04,546
At point X, the dead body is discovered.

199
00:19:07,587 --> 00:19:11,429
Next, at point Y, this is where you

200
00:19:11,509 --> 00:19:12,909
enter the name of the murderer.

201
00:19:16,390 --> 00:19:19,211
This comes up pretty early in the game.

202
00:19:23,753 --> 00:19:26,033
If you have the correct answer, in other words,

203
00:19:26,093 --> 00:19:28,914
if you're able to guess the murderer and you're right,

204
00:19:29,435 --> 00:19:31,095
you'll get the good ending, which is A.

205
00:19:33,809 --> 00:19:36,952
However, in most cases, you haven't collect enough clues

206
00:19:37,092 --> 00:19:40,035
to guess the murderer on the first try.

207
00:19:43,339 --> 00:19:45,701
So players will end up passing through Y

208
00:19:45,721 --> 00:19:54,430
and get to endings B, C, D, and so on.

209
00:19:56,904 --> 00:20:02,647
Unfortunately, those have tragic endings where all the characters are murdered, or you end

210
00:20:02,707 --> 00:20:07,590
up killing the heroine by mistake, and even vice versa.

211
00:20:13,254 --> 00:20:19,257
In order to avoid these endings, the players must return to point Y and enter the correct

212
00:20:19,398 --> 00:20:19,698
answer.

213
00:20:22,986 --> 00:20:28,329
But to do that, the player must collect hints and clues along the way that lead to those

214
00:20:28,449 --> 00:20:31,551
tragic B, C, and D endings.

215
00:20:36,974 --> 00:20:42,938
Once you've gathered enough clues and are ready to solve the case, you return to point

216
00:20:43,258 --> 00:20:43,338
Y.

217
00:20:44,178 --> 00:20:46,620
That's the basic flow in Kamaidachi no Yoru.

218
00:20:49,018 --> 00:20:54,022
The interesting thing about this float is that they're not using a flag at point Y.

219
00:20:54,042 --> 00:21:02,090
In any ordinary visual novel, it would work like this.

220
00:21:02,550 --> 00:21:09,416
You have a flag at B, and a flag at C, and a flag at D. Once you've gotten through all

221
00:21:09,476 --> 00:21:15,081
the flags, point Y will unlock, and you'll get the good ending at A.

222
00:21:18,137 --> 00:21:20,538
However, that's not how it works in this game.

223
00:21:24,619 --> 00:21:29,661
In an extreme case, if you're able to guess the correct name during your first playthrough,

224
00:21:31,122 --> 00:21:38,605
you'll get the good A ending without having to have to go through endings B, C, and D.

225
00:21:41,246 --> 00:21:44,867
So if there is no flag at point Y, what took its place?

226
00:21:46,852 --> 00:21:50,634
The answer is the memory that was embedded in the player's brain.

227
00:22:05,065 --> 00:22:08,348
Once the player gathers clues on path.

228
00:22:08,947 --> 00:22:15,873
B, C, and D, the main character of the game was able to go back to point Y and give the

229
00:22:15,913 --> 00:22:19,196
correct answer, thanks to the player's own memory.

230
00:22:20,837 --> 00:22:25,861
Normally in visual novels, that memory is stored onto the computer's memory as a piece

231
00:22:25,901 --> 00:22:26,381
of data.

232
00:22:28,163 --> 00:22:31,205
For example, were the clues picked up in path B?

233
00:22:31,726 --> 00:22:32,006
True.

234
00:22:32,667 --> 00:22:33,847
What about in path C?

235
00:22:34,208 --> 00:22:34,508
True.

236
00:22:35,269 --> 00:22:35,649
And D?

237
00:22:36,249 --> 00:22:36,470
True.

238
00:22:37,796 --> 00:22:42,138
